WEBVTT

00:01.627 --> 00:03.210
<i>- Last year,
a competition was created</i>

00:03.254 --> 00:05.587
<i>to test the nation's best
bladesmiths.</i>

00:05.631 --> 00:08.007
<i>Thousands responded,
and this year,</i>

00:08.050 --> 00:10.968
<i>craftsmen from all over the
country and all walks of life</i>

00:11.012 --> 00:13.887
<i>have come forward for their
chance to claim the title.</i>

00:13.931 --> 00:15.597
- I'm gonna be the next
"Forged in Fire" champion.

00:15.641 --> 00:16.932
- I want to win!

00:16.976 --> 00:18.392
- It would be
a life-changing moment.

00:18.436 --> 00:19.476
- Welcome to the Forge.

00:19.520 --> 00:21.687
<i>Now the Forge returns</i>

00:21.731 --> 00:24.940
<i>with challenges unlike anything
ever seen before.</i>

00:24.984 --> 00:26.692
You'll be using this.

00:26.736 --> 00:29.945
<i>Skill and ingenuity will be
pushed to the limit.</i>

00:29.989 --> 00:32.114
<i>Some will rise to the challenge,</i>

00:32.158 --> 00:33.949
<i>some will fall,</i>

00:33.993 --> 00:35.451
<i>but only the best
will be crowned</i>

00:35.494 --> 00:37.286
<i>"Forged in Fire" champions</i>

00:37.329 --> 00:40.289
<i>and take home $10,000.</i>

00:40.332 --> 00:43.292
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:43.335 --> 00:45.919
<i>¶ ¶</i>

00:45.963 --> 00:49.256
<i>[rock music]</i>

00:49.300 --> 00:50.799
<i>- Name's Kyle Gahagan.</i>

00:50.843 --> 00:54.011
I spent 4 1/2 years,
1st Ranger Battalion.

00:54.055 --> 00:56.972
<i>I did two tours in Afghanistan,
two in Iraq.</i>

00:57.016 --> 00:58.891
<i>It was a good
learning experience,</i>

00:58.934 --> 01:02.144
because if you want to be
a true custom knife maker,

01:02.188 --> 01:04.563
there's gonna be a sacrifice.

01:04.607 --> 01:07.608
<i>- My name is Ron Mizell.
I'm from Brooklyn, New York.</i>

01:07.651 --> 01:09.318
To me, bladesmith is a art form.

01:09.361 --> 01:13.489
People see me as a big,
giant, 280-pound guy

01:13.532 --> 01:15.991
<i>that's a little bit
intimidating.</i>

01:16.035 --> 01:17.576
<i>- My name is Bob Brandel.</i>

01:17.620 --> 01:19.036
<i>I'm very, very fierce,</i>

01:19.080 --> 01:21.121
and I'm very, very serious
about what I do.

01:21.165 --> 01:22.706
I'm terribly competitive
by nature,

01:22.750 --> 01:24.249
horribly so, in fact.

01:24.293 --> 01:26.335
<i>- My name's Tobin Nieto.</i>

01:26.378 --> 01:29.713
With every blade I make,
there's a little bit of myself.

01:29.757 --> 01:33.342
<i>Definitely ugly and dirty
and raggedy enough to be used,</i>

01:33.385 --> 01:35.010
and they end up looking like me.

01:35.054 --> 01:36.553
<i>[chuckles]</i>

01:36.597 --> 01:37.554
- Gentlemen,

01:37.598 --> 01:39.014
welcome to the Forge.

01:39.058 --> 01:40.766
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

01:40.810 --> 01:43.185
You are here to engage
in three rounds of competition

01:43.229 --> 01:46.271
designed to test
every aspect of blade making,

01:46.315 --> 01:49.358
from design to forging
to fit and finish.

01:49.401 --> 01:51.360
At the end of each round,
you will hand your work over

01:51.403 --> 01:53.362
to our panel of expert judges:

01:53.405 --> 01:56.615
American Bladesmith Society
Master Smith J. Neilson;

01:56.659 --> 01:59.201
next, historical weapons
re-creation specialist

01:59.245 --> 02:00.869
David Baker;

02:00.913 --> 02:03.705
finally, martial artist
and edged weapon specialist

02:03.749 --> 02:05.165
Doug Marcaida.

02:05.209 --> 02:06.708
They will decide
who will be declared

02:06.752 --> 02:08.377
the "Forged in Fire" champion

02:08.420 --> 02:11.713
and leave with a check
for $10,000.

02:11.757 --> 02:13.382
Today we're gonna make things

02:13.425 --> 02:15.050
a little bit more difficult.

02:15.094 --> 02:18.053
<i>¶ ¶</i>

02:18.097 --> 02:21.431
On this table are all of the
blades that failed to progress

02:21.475 --> 02:23.892
to round two last season.

02:23.936 --> 02:26.645
Your challenge is
to choose one and reforge it

02:26.689 --> 02:28.814
into a weapon of your own design

02:28.858 --> 02:30.566
and in your signature style,

02:30.609 --> 02:33.777
making it a fully
functional weapon.

02:33.821 --> 02:35.821
These failed blades
are a testament

02:35.865 --> 02:38.740
to how difficult
this round can be.

02:38.784 --> 02:40.909
<i>- Working with blades
that have been forged before,</i>

02:40.953 --> 02:42.786
<i>you're limited.</i>

02:42.830 --> 02:45.581
<i>You don't know exactly
what's happened to them.</i>

02:45.624 --> 02:47.916
It's not like working
with a raw piece of steel.

02:47.960 --> 02:50.919
- Also, we're letting
you know now:

02:50.963 --> 02:54.089
your finished weapons will
then be tested in a log chop...

02:54.133 --> 02:56.258
<i>¶ ¶</i>

02:56.302 --> 02:58.635
And a bread slice.

02:58.679 --> 03:00.470
The blades themselves
must fall within

03:00.514 --> 03:02.139
the following size parameters:

03:02.183 --> 03:05.767
<i>the length of the blade,
not including the tang,</i>

03:05.811 --> 03:08.103
<i>must not exceed 13 inches</i>

03:08.147 --> 03:10.772
<i>and must be more than 10 inches.</i>

03:10.816 --> 03:12.274
<i>The overall length of the weapon</i>

03:12.318 --> 03:15.027
<i>must not exceed 22 inches.</i>

03:15.070 --> 03:17.738
Additionally,
you must also incorporate

03:17.781 --> 03:19.948
an integral finger ring.

03:19.992 --> 03:23.410
<i>An integral finger ring
is a loop that is integrated</i>

03:23.454 --> 03:25.621
<i>somewhere within
the handle of the knife</i>

03:25.664 --> 03:28.290
<i>to provide added control
and a more secure grip</i>

03:28.334 --> 03:30.334
<i>while slashing or thrusting.</i>

03:30.377 --> 03:33.003
<i>- Trying to figure out how
to incorporate a finger ring</i>

03:33.047 --> 03:36.298
from failed blades
is gonna be a challenge.

03:36.342 --> 03:37.966
- You will have ten minutes
to work on your design.

03:38.010 --> 03:40.677
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

03:40.721 --> 03:44.681
Your ten-minute design
window starts... now.

03:44.725 --> 03:47.142
<i>[rock music]</i>

03:47.186 --> 03:49.561
<i>- Blade selection here
is gonna be very important</i>

03:49.605 --> 03:51.772
<i>if they're gonna add
that finger ring.</i>

03:51.815 --> 03:53.774
<i>- It's really about
that volume of the metal.</i>

03:53.817 --> 03:55.317
- Yes.

03:55.361 --> 03:57.569
What I'd be going
for is just more steel.

03:57.613 --> 03:59.404
<i>- I went
for the wakizashi blade.</i>

03:59.448 --> 04:02.324
<i>The tang being still
so thick and long enough,</i>

04:02.368 --> 04:04.701
<i>I knew I'd be able to draw
enough metal out</i>

04:04.745 --> 04:06.703
to have that wraparound
for the handle.

04:06.747 --> 04:09.748
<i>I'm making what's called
a blacksmith's knife.</i>

04:09.792 --> 04:11.792
<i>I decided to go
with the squirrel tail</i>

04:11.835 --> 04:13.585
<i>to make the ring guard.</i>

04:13.629 --> 04:15.170
<i>- I love that Bob's doing
a squirrel tail design</i>

04:15.214 --> 04:16.880
<i>to incorporate that finger ring,</i>

04:16.924 --> 04:18.840
<i>but it's not the easiest
to pull off.</i>

04:18.884 --> 04:20.550
<i>¶ ¶</i>

04:20.594 --> 04:22.636
<i>- My competitors
beat me to the table,</i>

04:22.680 --> 04:25.681
<i>so I pick up the biggest hunk
of steel that's still there.</i>

04:25.724 --> 04:29.559
<i>My signature blade is
a rather large chopping knife.</i>

04:29.603 --> 04:32.813
You can use a large chopping
knife for chopping trees,

04:32.856 --> 04:35.732
clearing brush, killing zombies,
or anything like that, you know?

04:35.776 --> 04:37.859
<i>[drum flourish]</i>

04:37.903 --> 04:39.569
<i>I decided to go
with a blade shape</i>

04:39.613 --> 04:42.030
<i>that's based off
of an oversized karambit</i>

04:42.074 --> 04:44.366
<i>and a large Roman falx.</i>

04:44.410 --> 04:46.451
<i>I thought, "Chopping, slicing...</i>

04:46.495 --> 04:48.203
<i>Let's put 'em together,
see what happens."</i>

04:48.247 --> 04:49.871
<i>- What we have here
is a guy who's chosen</i>

04:49.915 --> 04:51.707
<i>a canister Damascus blade.</i>

04:51.750 --> 04:53.041
Might not even know
that's what it is,

04:53.085 --> 04:54.459
but he could get
a brilliant finish on that

04:54.503 --> 04:55.836
<i>if he does a great job.</i>

04:55.879 --> 04:57.296
- Oh, absolutely, and he's got

04:57.339 --> 04:59.715
a lot of steel on there
to work with too.

04:59.758 --> 05:01.967
<i>- In order to forge
this finger ring,</i>

05:02.011 --> 05:05.345
<i>I grabbed a blade that's got
a lot of meat on the handle,</i>

05:05.389 --> 05:08.098
but I have no idea
what the material is.

05:08.142 --> 05:11.560
<i>I am best known
for bowie knives.</i>

05:11.603 --> 05:14.730
<i>Being in the military,
when I come into a situation</i>

05:14.773 --> 05:17.566
<i>that's not planned,
I've got to adapt and overcome.</i>

05:17.609 --> 05:20.235
That's what I've got to do here.

05:20.279 --> 05:21.737
<i>- The reason
I picked this dagger:</i>

05:21.780 --> 05:23.780
<i>it's the only blade
that was left</i>

05:23.824 --> 05:26.533
<i>with a little bit more
material that I needed.</i>

05:26.577 --> 05:30.120
<i>My signature blade
is the kukri blade.</i>

05:30.164 --> 05:33.081
<i>Kukri is what
the Nepal army used,</i>

05:33.125 --> 05:35.667
<i>and there's stories where
they will drop their gun,</i>

05:35.711 --> 05:37.419
and they will grab their kukri,

05:37.463 --> 05:38.795
<i>because they don't
trust the gun,</i>

05:38.839 --> 05:40.756
<i>but they trust the kukri knife.</i>

05:40.799 --> 05:44.343
- Gentlemen, your ten-minute
design window is now closed.

05:44.386 --> 05:47.763
Your three-hour forging
window starts... now.

05:47.806 --> 05:49.431
<i>[energetic music]</i>

05:49.475 --> 05:51.933
- All right.
- Here we go.

05:51.977 --> 05:53.518
<i>¶ ¶</i>

05:53.562 --> 05:55.187
<i>- My strengths
in bladesmithing are that</i>

05:55.230 --> 05:57.939
I can forge efficiently,
effectively,

05:57.983 --> 06:00.400
and pretty damn quick.

06:00.444 --> 06:02.444
- Bob, I'm curious, though...
'cause he's going with

06:02.488 --> 06:04.946
a squirrel tail design
for his handle...

06:04.990 --> 06:07.324
If that end of that
squirrel tail isn't connected

06:07.368 --> 06:09.117
to the main body of the blade,

06:09.161 --> 06:11.787
is that gonna stay together
while it's chopping?

06:11.830 --> 06:14.331
I hope he's gonna make it
a solid piece.

06:14.375 --> 06:15.957
<i>- From an aesthetic standpoint,</i>

06:16.001 --> 06:17.626
<i>there's just something
really cool to me</i>

06:17.669 --> 06:18.919
<i>about a knife that</i>

06:18.962 --> 06:20.837
<i>the handle, the tang,</i>

06:20.881 --> 06:24.883
the guard, and the blade
are all one homogenous unit.

06:24.927 --> 06:26.676
[clang]

06:26.720 --> 06:28.053
<i>[rock music]</i>

06:28.097 --> 06:29.721
- Whoo!

06:29.765 --> 06:31.306
<i>I feel bad that I have</i>

06:31.350 --> 06:33.058
<i>to take something
that somebody else made</i>

06:33.102 --> 06:34.810
<i>and basically destroy it,</i>

06:34.853 --> 06:38.313
but sometimes you got to destroy
things to create something new.

06:38.357 --> 06:40.190
<i>¶ ¶</i>

06:40.234 --> 06:41.817
- Tobin's showing
some remarkable skill

06:41.860 --> 06:43.610
with that air hammer.

06:43.654 --> 06:45.987
- He's doing a very good job.
- Very good control.

06:46.031 --> 06:47.906
- He's not running back and
forth; he's taking his time.

06:47.950 --> 06:49.408
But we've seen in the past,

06:49.451 --> 06:52.119
the guys that pace themselves
usually do well.

06:52.162 --> 06:53.328
- All right, we're still going.

06:53.372 --> 06:54.579
<i>I think I'm playing</i>

06:54.623 --> 06:56.331
the reverse psychology
card here.

06:56.375 --> 06:59.376
Like, I look like a big,
cuddly, furry teddy bear.

06:59.420 --> 07:01.878
<i>No one's gonna see me coming.</i>

07:01.922 --> 07:03.797
It's all part of the plan.

07:03.841 --> 07:05.465
[furnace roaring]

07:05.509 --> 07:08.009
<i>[funky music]</i>

07:08.053 --> 07:09.553
<i>- I'm not real happy
about working</i>

07:09.596 --> 07:11.513
<i>through other people's mistakes.</i>

07:11.557 --> 07:13.682
I don't know what issues
they've run into,

07:13.725 --> 07:15.684
what I'm looking at.

07:15.727 --> 07:19.187
The blade's roughly
2, 2 1/2 inches wide.

07:19.231 --> 07:21.523
<i>So it's a nice, beefy blade.</i>

07:21.567 --> 07:23.525
<i>With the challenge given,
I decide I need</i>

07:23.569 --> 07:26.069
<i>to thin that down a little bit.</i>

07:26.113 --> 07:29.030
- Kyle is the only one
whose design

07:29.074 --> 07:33.535
looked almost exactly like
what was already there.

07:33.579 --> 07:34.870
- And that blade had
cracks in it.

07:34.913 --> 07:36.872
He needs to fix that.

07:36.915 --> 07:39.583
- That thing doesn't hit hard.

07:39.626 --> 07:42.335
<i>- I used my military experience
in bladesmithing</i>

07:42.379 --> 07:45.547
<i>to start a blade therapy
organization.</i>

07:45.591 --> 07:47.048
<i>There's no charge.</i>

07:47.092 --> 07:48.717
<i>I keep my doors open
at all times</i>

07:48.760 --> 07:50.635
<i>and let veterans come in.</i>

07:50.679 --> 07:52.804
We'll work together
and work through things.

07:52.848 --> 07:54.723
Don't got a lot of metal
to work with.

07:54.766 --> 07:56.558
- Yeah, I cut it up.

07:56.602 --> 07:57.976
<i>[driving rock music]</i>

07:58.020 --> 07:59.561
<i>This is definitely frustrating,</i>

07:59.605 --> 08:01.062
<i>because the metal of that blade</i>

08:01.106 --> 08:02.772
<i>is really thin, and I don't know</i>

08:02.816 --> 08:05.150
what the previous owner
did with it.

08:05.194 --> 08:08.069
<i>I had to figure out
where to put the finger ring</i>

08:08.113 --> 08:09.321
<i>on the knife.</i>

08:09.364 --> 08:10.906
<i>¶ ¶</i>

08:10.949 --> 08:12.908
- Ron's really going to town.

08:12.951 --> 08:14.242
<i>- I don't know if he has
enough metal there</i>

08:14.286 --> 08:15.744
<i>to add a finger ring.</i>

08:15.787 --> 08:17.078
- I mean, he could
run over and say,

08:17.122 --> 08:18.788
"You know, I picked
the wrong piece,"

08:18.832 --> 08:21.374
drop it, toss it aside,
and grab that other blade.

08:21.418 --> 08:23.293
- Yeah, we're not
too far in yet.

08:23.337 --> 08:25.086
- Ron's struggling.
- Yeah.

08:25.130 --> 08:26.922
<i>¶ ¶</i>

08:26.965 --> 08:27.923
- Oh, man.

08:27.966 --> 08:30.091
- Two hours, gentlemen!

08:30.135 --> 08:32.219
You have two hours remaining!

08:32.262 --> 08:35.680
<i>[rock music]</i>

08:35.724 --> 08:37.766
- Sweating enough yet?
- Hell yeah.

08:37.809 --> 08:39.267
[both laugh]

08:39.311 --> 08:43.522
<i>¶ ¶</i>

08:44.900 --> 08:47.609
I am struggling
with the finger ring, man.

08:47.653 --> 08:49.110
[chuckles]

08:49.154 --> 08:50.946
I'm struggling
with the finger ring.

08:50.989 --> 08:52.781
<i>So I pick up the angle grinder,</i>

08:52.824 --> 08:54.991
cut the little nub of steel
that I need,

08:55.035 --> 08:56.993
<i>and decide I'm gonna go ahead
and bend it out</i>

08:57.037 --> 09:01.081
<i>so I can have enough steel
to do my final ring shape.</i>

09:01.124 --> 09:02.874
- I'm really liking
what Tobin's doing,

09:02.918 --> 09:06.836
but the hole in that ring
doesn't look very large.

09:06.880 --> 09:09.506
- I just hope that my skills
can pull me through.

09:09.550 --> 09:12.008
- Well, I'm also interested
to see where Bob's gonna go

09:12.052 --> 09:13.510
with that shape of that blade.

09:13.554 --> 09:15.220
- I was just gonna say
the exact same thing.

09:15.264 --> 09:18.890
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

09:18.934 --> 09:20.183
- Ahh.

09:21.687 --> 09:23.895
Oh, no! How the hell
did that happen?

09:23.939 --> 09:26.189
- Bob's got an issue
that I'm not sure what it is.

09:26.233 --> 09:28.316
<i>[rock music]</i>

09:28.360 --> 09:29.818
- It's not looking good.

09:29.861 --> 09:32.320
Aw, son of a bitch.

09:32.364 --> 09:34.573
<i>¶ ¶</i>

09:38.078 --> 09:40.996
<i>[rock music]</i>

09:41.039 --> 09:46.167
<i>¶ ¶</i>

09:46.211 --> 09:49.004
- Ahh.

09:49.047 --> 09:50.338
<i>As I'm grinding the knife,</i>

09:50.382 --> 09:52.716
I noticed that there was
a crack that was running

09:52.759 --> 09:54.676
<i>parallel to the edge.</i>

09:54.720 --> 09:57.220
Aw, son of a bitch.

09:58.390 --> 09:59.514
<i>¶ ¶</i>

09:59.558 --> 10:02.392
<i>I'm trying to grind it out.</i>

10:02.436 --> 10:03.602
<i>And it's going away.</i>

10:03.645 --> 10:07.063
Well, my friends,
crisis averted.

10:07.107 --> 10:08.565
- One hour, gentlemen!

10:08.609 --> 10:11.234
You have one hour remaining!

10:11.278 --> 10:14.362
<i>[rock music]</i>

10:14.406 --> 10:16.531
<i>¶ ¶</i>

10:16.575 --> 10:20.035
<i>We've got Ron, who's been on
the grinder for quite a while.</i>

10:20.078 --> 10:23.246
- I'm grinding this blade
to make this knife sharp.

10:23.290 --> 10:24.581
[belt snaps]

10:24.625 --> 10:25.999
- Whoa.
- Whoa, belt break.

10:26.043 --> 10:28.376
- Blowout!
[chuckling]

10:28.420 --> 10:30.754
- If you put too much
pressure on those belts,

10:30.797 --> 10:33.465
that glue seam will bust loose.

10:33.508 --> 10:34.758
<i>- I'm worried.</i>

10:34.801 --> 10:36.426
Time is running down.

10:36.470 --> 10:39.387
<i>I'm hoping the knife
was gonna be done.</i>

10:39.431 --> 10:40.347
<i>¶ ¶</i>

10:40.390 --> 10:41.598
- 15 minutes!

10:41.642 --> 10:43.933
15 minutes remaining!
- Argh.

10:43.977 --> 10:47.896
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

10:47.939 --> 10:49.397
- Kyle's adding clay.

10:49.441 --> 10:51.775
He's gonna do a clay quench.

10:51.818 --> 10:53.443
It gives it
a lot more character.

10:53.487 --> 10:56.112
- This is the kind
of attention to detail

10:56.156 --> 10:57.781
that propels a guy
into the next round.

10:57.824 --> 10:59.407
- Exactly.

10:59.451 --> 11:01.743
- Gentlemen, you have
one minute remaining!

11:01.787 --> 11:05.372
<i>¶ ¶</i>

11:05.415 --> 11:06.581
- Got to hurry.

11:06.625 --> 11:07.832
- Moment of truth.

11:07.876 --> 11:11.586
- Ten, nine, eight,

11:11.630 --> 11:15.423
seven, six, five,

11:15.467 --> 11:19.594
four, three, two, one.

11:19.638 --> 11:22.597
Time is up!
Your work is complete!

11:22.641 --> 11:26.851
Place your blades on your anvils
and step back!

11:26.895 --> 11:28.436
<i>[rock music]</i>

11:28.480 --> 11:30.563
<i>- It's definitely
a unique design.</i>

11:30.607 --> 11:34.567
<i>I think, overall,
I did pretty well.</i>

11:34.611 --> 11:36.277
<i>- Time's up.</i>

11:36.321 --> 11:39.531
I'm looking at that ring,
just not happy about it,

11:39.574 --> 11:41.866
but I did the best I can.

11:41.910 --> 11:43.451
I pushed through.

11:43.495 --> 11:44.786
<i>I'm happy overall.</i>

11:44.830 --> 11:47.997
<i>¶ ¶</i>

11:48.041 --> 11:49.874
- Bladesmiths,
you had three hours

11:49.918 --> 11:52.293
to transform a failed blade
from last season

11:52.337 --> 11:54.462
into a weapon
of your signature style

11:54.506 --> 11:56.715
with an integral finger ring.

11:56.758 --> 12:00.677
Tobin, please present your blade
to the judges.

12:00.721 --> 12:02.887
<i>- Tobin, I like
what you did here.</i>

12:02.931 --> 12:05.014
<i>You did leave a lot more meat
